66
0:03:32.851,000 --> 0:03:35,000
seem to be really undone by their gifts, you know.

67
0:03:36.227,000 --> 0:03:38,000
Norman Mailer, just before he died, last interview, he said,

68
0:03:39.126,000 --> 0:03:43,000
"Every one of my books has killed me a little more."

69
0:03:43.227,000 --> 0:03:46,000
An extraordinary statement to make about your life's work.

70
0:03:46.826,000 --> 0:03:48,000
But we don't even blink when we hear somebody say this,

71
0:03:49.786,000 --> 0:03:51,000
because we've heard that kind of stuff for so long

72
0:03:52.392,000 --> 0:03:55,000
and somehow we've completely internalized and accepted collectively

73
0:03:56.393,000 --> 0:04:,000
this notion that creativity and suffering are somehow inherently linked

74
0:04:01.06,000 --> 0:04:06,000
and that artistry, in the end, will always ultimately lead to anguish.

75
0:04:06.126,000 --> 0:04:08,000
And the question that I want to ask everybody here today

76
0:04:08.817,000 --> 0:04:1,000
is are you guys all cool with that idea?

77
0:04:11.334,000 --> 0:04:13,000
Are you comfortable with that?

78
0:04:13.541,000 --> 0:04:16,000
Because you look at it even from an inch away and, you know --

79
0:04:16.565,000 --> 0:04:19,000
I'm not at all comfortable with that assumption.

80
0:04:19.692,000 --> 0:04:2,000
I think it's odious.

81
0:04:21.178,000 --> 0:04:22,000
