82
0:04:23.131,000 --> 0:04:25,000
and I don't want to see it perpetuated into the next century.

83
0:04:26.06,000 --> 0:04:29,000
I think it's better if we encourage our great creative minds to live.

84
0:04:29.934,000 --> 0:04:34,000
And I definitely know that, in my case -- in my situation --

85
0:04:35.709,000 --> 0:04:4,000
it would be very dangerous for me to start sort of leaking down that dark path

86
0:04:40.872,000 --> 0:04:41,000
of assumption,

87
0:04:42.093,000 --> 0:04:46,000
particularly given the circumstance that I'm in right now in my career.

88
0:04:46.246,000 --> 0:04:48,000
Which is -- you know, like check it out,

89
0:04:48.785,000 --> 0:04:5,000
I'm pretty young, I'm only about 40 years old.

90
0:04:51,000 --> 0:04:54,000
I still have maybe another four decades of work left in me.

91
0:04:54.294,000 --> 0:04:58,000
And it's exceedingly likely that anything I write from this point forward

92
0:04:58.811,000 --> 0:05:,000
is going to be judged by the world as the work that came after

93
0:05:01.788,000 --> 0:05:04,000
the freakish success of my last book, right?

94
0:05:05.111,000 --> 0:05:08,000
I should just put it bluntly, because we're all sort of friends here now --

95
0:05:09.073,000 --> 0:05:13,000
it's exceedingly likely that my greatest success is behind me.

96
0:05:13.354,000 --> 0:05:15,000
So Jesus, what a thought!

97
0:05:15.554,000 --> 0:05:17,000
That's the kind of thought that could lead a person

98
0:05:17.984,000 --> 0:05:19,000
to start drinking gin at nine o'clock in the morning,

99
0:05:20.612,000 --> 0:05:22,000
and I don't want to go there.

100
0:05:23.549,000 --> 0:05:24,000
(Laughter)

101
0:05:24.607,000 --> 0:05:26,000
I would prefer to keep doing this work that I love.

102
0:05:27.061,000 --> 0:05:3,000
And so, the question becomes, how?

103
0:05:30.399,000 --> 0:05:32,000
And so, it seems to me, upon a lot of reflection,

104
0:05:33.283,000 --> 0:05:36,000
that the way that I have to work now, in order to continue writing,

105
0:05:36.648,000 --> 0:05:39,000
is that I have to create some sort of protective psychological construct, right?

106
0:05:40.482,000 --> 0:05:43,000
I have to sort of find some way to have a safe distance

107
0:05:43.982,000 --> 0:05:47,000
between me, as I am writing, and my very natural anxiety

108
0:05:48.867,000 --> 0:05:51,000
about what the reaction to that writing is going to be, from now on.

109
0:05:52.732,000 --> 0:05:54,000
And, as I've been looking, over the last year,

110
0:05:55.143,000 --> 0:05:56,000
for models for how to do that,

111
0:05:57,000 --> 0:05:59,000
I've been sort of looking across time,

112
0:05:59.148,000 --> 0:06:01,000
and I've been trying to find other societies

113
0:06:01.25,000 --> 0:06:04,000
to see if they might have had better and saner ideas than we have

114
0:06:05,000 --> 0:06:07,000
about how to help creative people

115
0:06:07.227,000 --> 0:06:1,000
sort of manage the inherent emotional risks of creativity.

116
0:06:11.033,000 --> 0:06:15,000
And that search has led me to ancient Greece and ancient Rome.

117
0:06:16.048,000 --> 0:06:18,000
So stay with me, because it does circle around and back.

118
0:06:18.739,000 --> 0:06:2,000
But, ancient Greece and ancient Rome --

119
0:06:20.895,000 --> 0:06:22,000
people did not happen to believe that creativity

120
0:06:23.461,000 --> 0:06:25,000
came from human beings back then, OK?

121
0:06:25.879,000 --> 0:06:29,000
People believed that creativity was this divine attendant spirit

122
0:06:30.338,000 --> 0:06:33,000
that came to human beings from some distant and unknowable source,

123
0:06:34.339,000 --> 0:06:36,000
for distant and unknowable reasons.

124
0:06:36.788,000 --> 0:06:41,000
The Greeks famously called these divine attendant spirits of creativity "daemons."

125
0:06:42.039,000 --> 0:06:45,000
Socrates, famously, believed that he had a daemon

126
0:06:45.139,000 --> 0:06:47,000
who spoke wisdom to him from afar.

127
0:06:47.596,000 --> 0:06:48,000
The Romans had the same idea,

128
0:06:49.213,000 --> 0:06:53,000
but they called that sort of disembodied creative spirit a genius.

129
0:06:53.823,000 --> 0:06:55,000
Which is great, because the Romans did not actually think

130
0:06:56.562,000 --> 0:06:58,000
that a genius was a particularly clever individual.

131
0:06:59.356,000 --> 0:07:02,000
They believed that a genius was this, sort of magical divine entity,

132
0:07:03.039,000 --> 0:07:08,000
who was believed to literally live in the walls of an artist's studio,

133
0:07:08.361,000 --> 0:07:1,000
kind of like Dobby the house elf,

134
0:07:10.905,000 --> 0:07:11,000
and who would come out

135
0:07:12.443,000 --> 0:07:14,000
and sort of invisibly assist the artist with their work

136
0:07:15.069,000 --> 0:07:17,000
and would shape the outcome of that work.

137
0:07:17.538,000 --> 0:07:2,000
So brilliant -- there it is, right there, that distance that I'm talking about --

138
0:07:21.42,000 --> 0:07:25,000
that psychological construct to protect you from the results of your work.

139
0:07:25.622,000 --> 0:07:28,000
And everyone knew that this is how it functioned, right?

140
0:07:29.23,000 --> 0:07:31,000
So the ancient artist was protected from certain things,

141
0:07:31.921,000 --> 0:07:33,000
like, for example, too much narcissism, right?

142
0:07:34.322,000 --> 0:07:37,000
If your work was brilliant, you couldn't take all the credit for it,

143
0:07:37.537,000 --> 0:07:4,000
everybody knew that you had this disembodied genius who had helped you.

144
0:07:41.256,000 --> 0:07:44,000
If your work bombed, not entirely your fault, you know?

145
0:07:44.625,000 --> 0:07:46,000
Everyone knew your genius was kind of lame.

146
0:07:47.143,000 --> 0:07:48,000
(Laughter)

147
0:07:48.201,000 --> 0:07:51,000
And this is how people thought about creativity in the West

148
0:07:51.723,000 --> 0:07:52,000
for a really long time.

149
0:07:53.055,000 --> 0:07:55,000
And then the Renaissance came and everything changed,

150
0:07:55.655,000 --> 0:07:57,000
and we had this big idea, and the big idea was,

151
0:07:57.97,000 --> 0:08:,000
let's put the individual human being at the center of the universe

152
0:08:01.189,000 --> 0:08:02,000
above all gods and mysteries,

153
0:08:02.754,000 --> 0:08:04,000
and there's no more room for mystical creatures

154
0:08:05.063,000 --> 0:08:06,000
who take dictation from the divine.

155
0:08:06.855,000 --> 0:08:08,000
And it's the beginning of rational humanism,

156
0:08:08.99,000 --> 0:08:1,000
and people started to believe that creativity

157
0:08:11.157,000 --> 0:08:13,000
came completely from the self of the individual.

158
0:08:13.521,000 --> 0:08:14,000
And for the first time in history,

159
0:08:15.371,000 --> 0:08:2,000
you start to hear people referring to this or that artist as being a genius,

160
0:08:20.482,000 --> 0:08:21,000
rather than having a genius.

161
0:08:22.323,000 --> 0:08:25,000
And I got to tell you, I think that was a huge error.

162
0:08:25.647,000 --> 0:08:29,000
