that's exactly what my creative process is like.

234
0:11:52.779,000 --> 0:11:55,000
(Laughter)

235
0:11:56.392,000 --> 0:11:59,000
That's not at all what my creative process is -- I'm not the pipeline!

236
0:11:59.758,000 --> 0:12:01,000
I'm a mule, and the way that I have to work

237
0:12:01.812,000 --> 0:12:03,000
is I have to get up at the same time every day,

238
0:12:04.079,000 --> 0:12:06,000
and sweat and labor and barrel through it really awkwardly.

239
0:12:06.913,000 --> 0:12:07,000
But even I, in my mulishness,

240
0:12:08.776,000 --> 0:12:11,000
even I have brushed up against that thing, at times.

241
0:12:12.644,000 --> 0:12:14,000
And I would imagine that a lot of you have too.

242
0:12:14.907,000 --> 0:12:17,000
You know, even I have had work or ideas come through me from a source

243
0:12:18.212,000 --> 0:12:2,000
that I honestly cannot identify.

244
0:12:20.723,000 --> 0:12:21,000
And what is that thing?

245
0:12:22.319,000 --> 0:12:26,000
And how are we to relate to it in a way that will not make us lose our minds,

246
0:12:26.357,000 --> 0:12:28,000
but, in fact, might actually keep us sane?

247
0:12:29.243,000 --> 0:12:32,000
And for me, the best contemporary example that I have of how to do that

248
0:12:33.022,000 --> 0:12:35,000
is the musician Tom Waits,

249
0:12:35.354,000 --> 0:12:39,000
who I got to interview several years ago on a magazine assignment.

250
0:12:39.895,000 --> 0:12:4,000
And we were talking about this,

251
0:12:41.396,000 --> 0:12:44,000
and you know, Tom, for most of his life, he was pretty much the embodiment

252
0:12:44.957,000 --> 0:12:46,000
of the tormented contemporary modern artist,

253
0:12:47.077,000 --> 0:12:49,000
trying to control and manage and dominate

254
0:12:49.404,000 --> 0:12:51,000
these sort of uncontrollable creative impulses

255
0:12:51.878,000 --> 0:12:52,000
that were totally internalized.

256
0:12:53.765,000 --> 0:12:54,000
But then he got older, he got calmer,

257
0:12:55.77,000 --> 0:12:57,000
and one day he was driving down the freeway in Los Angeles,

258
0:12:58.693,000 --> 0:12:59,000
and this is when it all changed for him.

259
0:13:00.629,000 --> 0:13:02,000
And he's speeding along, and all of a sudden

260
0:13:02.719,000 --> 0:13:05,000
he hears this little fragment of melody,

261
0:13:06.265,000 --> 0:13:1,000
that comes into his head as inspiration often comes, elusive and tantalizing,

262
0:13:10.294,000 --> 0:13:12,000
and he wants it, it's gorgeous,

263
0:13:12.422,000 --> 0:13:14,000
and he longs for it, but he has no way to get it.

264
0:13:14.747,000 --> 0:13:17,000
He doesn't have a piece of paper, or a pencil, or a tape recorder.

265
0:13:17.922,000 --> 0:13:2,000
So he starts to feel all of that old anxiety start to rise in him

266
0:13:21.006,000 --> 0:13:22,000
like, "I'm going to lose this thing,

267
0:13:22.771,000 --> 0:13:24,000
and I'll be be haunted by this song forever.

268
0:13:24.891,000 --> 0:13:25,000
I'm not good enough, and I can't do it."

269
0:13:26.82,000 --> 0:13:28,000
And instead of panicking, he just stopped.

270
0:13:28.854,000 --> 0:13:32,000
He just stopped that whole mental process and he did something completely novel.

271
0:13:32.996,000 --> 0:13:34,000
He just looked up at the sky, and he said,

272
0:13:35.479,000 --> 0:13:37,000
"Excuse me, can you not see that I'm driving?"

273
0:13:38.493,000 --> 0:13:41,000
(Laughter)

274
0:13:42.194,000 --> 0:13:44,000
"Do I look like I can write down a song right now?

275
0:13:44.928,000 --> 0:13:47,000
If you really want to exist, come back at a more opportune moment

276
0:13:48.773,000 --> 0:13:49,000
when I can take care of you.

277
0:13:50.435,000 --> 0:13:53,000
Otherwise, go bother somebody else today.

278
0:13:53.512,000 --> 0:13:56,000
Go bother Leonard Cohen."

279
0:13:56.808,000 --> 0:13:59,000
And his whole work process changed after that.

280
0:13:59.94,000 --> 0:14:02,000
Not the work, the work was still oftentimes as dark as ever.

281
0:14:03.548,000 --> 0:14:06,000
But the process, and the heavy anxiety around it

282
0:14:06.607,000 --> 0:14:08,000
was released when he took the genie, the genius out of him

283
0:14:09.554,000 --> 0:14:12,000
where it was causing nothing but trouble, and released it back where it came from,

284
0:14:13.465,000 --> 0:14:16,000
and realized that this didn't have to be this internalized, tormented thing.

285
0:14:17.126,000 --> 0:14:2,000
It could be this peculiar, wondrous, bizarre collaboration,

286
0:14:20.264,000 --> 0:14:24,000
kind of conversation between Tom and the strange, external thing

287
0:14:24.396,000 --> 0:14:25,000
that was not quite Tom.

288
0:14:26.629,000 --> 0:14:28,000
When I heard that story, it started to shift a little bit

289
0:14:29.336,000 --> 0:14:32,000
the way that I worked too, and this idea already saved me once.

290
0:14:32.365,000 --> 0:14:35,000
It saved me when I was in the middle of writing "Eat, Pray, Love,"

291
0:14:35.493,000 --> 0:14:37,000
and I fell into one of those sort of pits of despair

292
0:14:38.026,000 --> 0:14:41,000
that we all fall into when we're working on something and it's not coming

293
0:14:41.506,000 --> 0:14:45,000
and you start to think this is going to be a disaster, the worst book ever written.

294
0:14:45.69,000 --> 0:14:47,000
Not just bad, but the worst book ever written.

295
0:14:48.064,000 --> 0:14:51,000
And I started to think I should just dump this project.

296
0:14:51.479,000 --> 0:14:54,000
But then I remembered Tom talking to the open air

297
0:14:54.554,000 --> 0:14:56,000
and I tried it.

298
0:14:56.602,000 --> 0:14:58,000
So I just lifted my face up from the manuscript

299
0:14:59.094,000 --> 0:15:01,000
and I directed my comments to an empty corner of the room.

300
0:15:02.024,000 --> 0:15:05,000
And I said aloud, "Listen you, thing,

301
0:15:05.602,000 --> 0:15:08,000
you and I both know that if this book isn't brilliant

302
0:15:08.8,000 --> 0:15:09,000
that is not entirely my fault, right?

303
0:15:10.601,000 --> 0:15:13,000
Because you can see that I am putting everything I have into this,

304
0:15:13.857,000 --> 0:15:14,000
I don't have any more than this.

305
0:15:15.496,000 --> 0:15:18,000
If you want it to be better, you've got to show up and do your part of the deal.

306
0:15:19.305,000 --> 0:15:21,000
But if you don't do that, you know what, the hell with it.

307
0:15:22.146,000 --> 0:15:24,000
I'm going to keep writing anyway because that's my job.

308
0:15:24.852,000 --> 0:15:26,000
And I would please like the record to reflect today

309
0:15:27.312,000 --> 0:15:28,000
that I showed up for my part of the job."

310
0:15:29.334,000 --> 0:15:31,000
(Laughter)

311
0:15:32.349,000 --> 0:15:34,000
Because --

312
0:15:34.436,000 --> 0:15:36,000
(Applause)

313
0:15:36.51,000 --> 0:15:38,000
Because in the end it's like this, OK --

314
0:15:38.682,000 --> 0:15:4,000
centuries ago in the deserts of North Africa,

315
0:15:41.083,000 --> 0:15:45,000
people used to gather for these moonlight dances of sacred dance and music

316
0:15:45.75,000 --> 0:15:47,000
that would go on for hours and hours, until dawn.

317
0:15:48.454,000 --> 0:15:51,000
They were always magnificent, because the dancers were professionals

318
0:15:51.698,000 --> 0:15:52,000
and they were terrific, right?

319
0:15:53.152,000 --> 0:15:56,000
But every once in a while, very rarely, something would happen,

320
0:15:56.473,000 --> 0:15:59,000
and one of these performers would actually become transcendent.

321
0:15:59.985,000 --> 0:16:01,000
And I know you know what I'm talking about,

322
0:16:02.269,000 --> 0:16:04,000
because I know you've all seen, at some point in your life,

323
0:16:05.089,000 --> 0:16:06,000
a performance like this.

324
0:16:06.389,000 --> 0:16:07,000
It was like time would stop,

325
0:16:08.318,000 --> 0:16:1,000
and the dancer would sort of step through some kind of portal

326
0:16:11.247,000 --> 0:16:12,000
and he wasn't doing anything different

327
0:16:13.151,000 --> 0:16:15,000
than he had ever done, 1,000 nights before,

328
0:16:15.184,000 --> 0:16:16,000
but everything would align.

329
0:16:16.935,000 --> 0:16:19,000
And all of a sudden, he would no longer appear to be merely human.

330
0:16:20.102,000 --> 0:16:22,000
He would be lit from within, and lit from below

331
0:16:22.501,000 --> 0:16:25,000
and all lit up on fire with divinity.

332
0:16:26.291,000 --> 0:16:28,000
And when this happened, back then,

333
0:16:28.436,000 --> 0:16:32,000
people knew it for what it was, you know, they called it by its name.

334
0:16:32.652,000 --> 0:16:35,000
They would put their hands together and they would start to chant,

335
0:16:35.819,000 --> 0:16:38,000
"Allah, Allah, Allah, God, God, God."

336
0:16:39.384,000 --> 0:16:42,000
That's God, you know.

337
0:16:42.486,000 --> 0:16:44,000
Curious historical footnote:

338
0:16:45.166,000 --> 0:16:49,000
when the Moors invaded southern Spain, they took this custom with them

339
0:16:50.007,000 --> 0:16:52,000
and the pronunciation changed over the centuries

340
0:16:52.317,000 --> 0:16:54,000
from "Allah, Allah, Allah," to "Olé, olé, olé,"

341
0:16:55.117,000 --> 0:16:58,000
which you still hear in bullfights and in flamenco dances.

342
0:16:58.291,000 --> 0:17:01,000
In Spain, when a performer has done something impossible and magic,

343
0:17:01.944,000 --> 0:17:04,000
"Allah, olé, olé, Allah, magnificent, bravo,"

344
0:17:05.093,000 --> 0:17:07,000
incomprehensible, there it is -- a glimpse of God.

345
0:17:08.547,000 --> 0:17:1,000
Which is great, because we need that.

346
0:17:10.669,000 --> 0:17:13,000
But, the tricky bit comes the next morning,

347
0:17:14.52,000 --> 0:17:17,000
for the dancer himself, when he wakes up and discovers

348
0:17:17.947,000 --> 0:17:2,000
that it's Tuesday at 11 a.m., and he's no longer a glimpse of God.

349
0:17:21.394,000 --> 0:17:24,000
He's just an aging mortal with really bad knees,

350
0:17:24.886,000 --> 0:17:28,000
and maybe he's never going to ascend to that height again.

351
0:17:29.126,000 --> 0:17:32,000
And maybe nobody will ever chant God's name again as he spins,

352
0:17:32.853,000 --> 0:17:34,000
and what is he then to do with the rest of his life?

353
0:17:35.711,000 --> 0:17:36,000
This is hard.

354
0:17:37.093,000 --> 0:17:39,000
This is one of the most painful reconciliations to make

355
0:17:39.935,000 --> 0:17:41,000
in a creative life.

356
0:17:42.026,000 --> 0:17:45,000
But maybe it doesn't have to be quite so full of anguish

357
0:17:45.209,000 --> 0:17:48,000
if you never happened to believe, in the first place,

358
0:17:48.476,000 --> 0:17:52,000
that the most extraordinary aspects of your being came from you.

359
0:17:52.581,000 --> 0:17:54,000
But maybe if you just believed that they were on loan to you

360
0:17:55.442,000 --> 0:17:58,000
from some unimaginable source for some exquisite portion of your life

361
0:17:59.05,000 --> 0:18:01,000
to be passed along when you're finished,

362
0:18:01.09,000 --> 0:18:02,000
with somebody else.

363
0:18:02.941,000 --> 0:18:06,000
And, you know, if we think about it this way, it starts to change everything.

364
0:18:07.746,000 --> 0:18:08,000
This is how I've started to think,

365
0:18:09.61,000 --> 0:18:12,000
and this is certainly how I've been thinking in the last few months

366
0:18:12.959,000 --> 0:18:14,000
as I've been working on the book that will soon be published,

367
0:18:15.888,000 --> 0:18:18,000
as the dangerously, frighteningly over-anticipated follow up

368
0:18:19.443,000 --> 0:18:21,000
to my freakish success.

369
0:18:22.103,000 --> 0:18:24,000
And what I have to sort of keep telling myself

370
0:18:25.026,000 --> 0:18:29,000
when I get really psyched out about that is don't be afraid.

371
0:18:29.226,000 --> 0:18:32,000
Don't be daunted. Just do your job.

372
0:18:32.575,000 --> 0:18:35,000
Continue to show up for your piece of it, whatever that might be.

373
0:18:35.695,000 --> 0:18:37,000
If your job is to dance, do your dance.

374
0:18:38.46,000 --> 0:18:41,000
If the divine, cockeyed genius assigned to your case

375
0:18:42.425,000 --> 0:18:47,000
decides to let some sort of wonderment be glimpsed, for just one moment

376
0:18:47.509,000 --> 0:18:49,000
through your efforts, then "Olé!"

377
0:18:50.213,000 --> 0:18:52,000
And if not, do your dance anyhow.

378
0:18:53.148,000 --> 0:18:54,000
And "Olé!" to you, nonetheless.

379
0:18:54.829,000 --> 0:18:56,000
I believe this and I feel that we must teach it.

380
0:18:57.139,000 --> 0:18:58,000
"Olé!" to you, nonetheless,

381
0:18:58.617,000 --> 0:19:01,000
just for having the sheer human love and stubbornness

382
0:19:01.93,000 --> 0:19:02,000
to keep showing up.

383
0:19:03.775,000 --> 0:19:04,000
Thank you.

384
0:19:05.45,000 --> 0:19:07,000
(Applause)

385
0:19:07.525,000 --> 0:19:08,000
Thank you.

386
0:19:09.016,000 --> 0:19:12,000
(Applause)

